method:
Well, this is hard to say... I would say, that my method to answer those specific questions was not entirely based on my knowledge and experience in foreign and security policy. It rather took into account to given time frame and an estimation, if something seems feasible within this two months window. For example: I would definately see a high probability, that the US might impose new sanctions on Iran and abandon the current Agreement. I just do not think, that it will be possible to process this until April 24. 

Questions on specific events (such as terrorist-attacks) are more tough though to forecast. As we now, even our Intelligence Community can not do that. Therefore, my forecasts here are more based on mathematics, meaning that in general, a terrorist attack ist, despite being a modern threat, rather unlikely at a given time or place. Here again, the time frame plays are role: If the question would be "Do you think, there will be a devestating Terrorist attack somewhere in Western Europe in the next 10 years", I would definately give it a 95% rate of probability. But if the question is, if I think there will be devestating Terrorist attack in City X tomorrow, that probability is very low, statistically speaking. This is way I rather gave low scores on questions related to such events.

method: In virtually every decision they make, executives today consider some kind of forecast. Sound predictions of demands and trends are no longer luxury items, but a necessity, if managers are to cope with seasonality, sudden changes in demand levels, price-cutting maneuvers of the competition, strikes, and large swings of the economy. Forecasting can help them deal with these troubles; but it can help them more, the more they know about the general principles of forecasting, what it can and cannot do for them currently, and which techniques are suited to their needs of the moment. Here the authors try to explain the potential of forecasting to managers, focusing special attention on sales forecasting for products of Corning Glass Works as these have matured through the product life cycle. Also included is a rundown of forecasting techniques

method:
I am no expert on many of these question, as I'm usually dealing with the Far East and not with America or the Middle East, but I was too lazy to do actual research apart from the newspaper coverage I'm reading anyway, so I relied mostly on intuition and on inferring knowledge from other areas.
Let's take the cease-fire and peace treaty negotiations as an example.
I read some coverage about the negotiations in Syria and I know that the rebels have lost a lot of its ground, but I'm no expert. Yet I can infer knowledge - from East Asian or European history and also from Paul Collier's "The bottom billion"), who actually analyzed civil wars in a statisical way. This, together with intuition replacing a more thorough analysis leads me to the following conclusions:
- It's rather likely that cease-fire agreements are broken, if at least one party has some interest in continuing the fights if there is no clear victor (e. g. Syrian government), or the notion of Collier that civil wars are very likely to break out again. Also, terrorist attacks are likely in Syria and they are likely to jeopardize cease-fire agreements.
- If a cease-fire agreement is broken, a peace treaty is less likely to follow. Even if the cease-fire agreement is maintained and the balance of power is clear (e. g. Japan 1945), peace treaty negotiations usually take a lot of time (Treaty of San Francisco with Japan & USA) and are often not done at all (cf. Korean War or that there's no peace treaty between Russia and Japan yet), especially if one party is not a recognized government or one party doesn't recognize the other (e. g. FARC agreement, Taiwan/ PRC China). Finally, the presence of the Islamic State as an actor, virtually noone recognizes, lowers the probability of peace agreements too...
Yet, I believe in surprises in history and I hope the 2% probability of some peace treaty comes true.
